            "new_string": "## P6: Kernel Subsystem Visualization (Educational Web UI)\n\nGoal: Transform kbox's web dashboard from a telemetry-only tool into an\ninteractive, educational visualization of Linux kernel subsystem interactions.\nUse the house-cross-section narrative style from the Linux comic\n(hackmd.io/@sysprog/linux-comic), with cute penguin characters animated in the\nstyle of star-office-ui-v2 and tinyclaw's pixel-art office scenes.\n\nThis is kbox's differentiator vs containers/VMs: we intercept every syscall and\nroute it through LKL, so we can show REAL kernel activity -- not static diagrams,\nbut live subsystem interactions driven by actual guest behavior.\n\n### Design Concept\n\nA pixel-art \"kernel house\" cross-section occupies the left/center of the\ndashboard. Each room represents a kernel subsystem. Penguin characters move\nbetween rooms as syscalls flow through the system. The existing telemetry\npanels (charts, gauges, event feed) remain on the right side or in tabs.\n\n```\n┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────┐\n│  User Space (attic)                             │\n│  [guest process penguins making syscalls]       │\n├─────────────────────────────────────────────────┤\n│  Syscall Gate                                   │\n│  [seccomp-unotify desk, penguin dispatcher]     │\n├──────────┬──────────┬──────────┬────────────────┤\n│ VFS Room │ Process  │ Memory   │ Network        │\n│ [filing  │ Mgmt     │ Mgmt     │ [mailroom      │\n│  cabinet │ [scheduler│[page     │  penguins,     │\n│  penguin]│  penguin] │ penguin] │  SLIRP desk]   │\n├──────────┴──────────┴──────────┴────────────────┤\n│  Block I/O Basement                             │\n│  [ext4 storage penguin, LKL disk]               │\n└─────────────────────────────────────────────────┘\n```\n\n### Rooms (Subsystems) and What Drives Them\n\nEach room lights up / shows activity based on real kbox telemetry:\n\n| Room | Subsystem | Data source | Activity trigger |\n|------|-----------|-------------|------------------|\n| Attic | User space | SSE events (pid, syscall name) | Any syscall from guest |\n| Gate | seccomp dispatch | counters.disp_continue/return/enosys | Every intercepted syscall |\n| VFS | Virtual filesystem | family.file_io + family.dir | open, read, write, stat, readdir |\n| Process | Scheduler/process | family.scheduler + context_switches | clone, execve, sched_yield, exit |\n| Memory | Memory management | mem_*, pgfault, pgmajfault | mmap, brk, page faults |\n| Network | Networking | family.other (socket/connect/sendto) | socket, connect, sendmsg |\n| Basement | Block I/O | LKL /proc/diskstats (future) | read/write on ext4 files |\n| FD Vault | FD table | fd_table_used, fd_table_max | open, close, dup2, pipe |\n\n### Character Design\n\nAdapt penguin sprites from tinyclaw's character sprite sheet system (7x3\nframes: idle/walk/type/celebrate/error/sleep, 3 directions). Restyle as\nTux-like penguins with role-specific accessories:\n\n| Character | Role | Visual cue |\n|-----------|------|------------|\n| Dispatcher Tux | seccomp gate | Wears a sorting hat, routes syscalls |\n| File Tux | VFS operations | Carries folders, opens filing cabinets |\n| Sched Tux | Process scheduler | Holds a stopwatch, juggles process balls |\n| Memory Tux | Page allocator | Stacks/unstacks memory blocks |\n| Net Tux | Network stack | Carries envelopes (packets) |\n| Storage Tux | Block I/O / ext4 | Pushes cart of disk blocks |\n| Guest penguin(s) | Tracee processes | One per active PID, smaller/lighter color |\n\nSpeech bubbles (tinyclaw-style) show what is happening:\n- Dispatcher: \"openat(/etc/passwd) → VFS Room\"\n- File Tux: \"Reading 4096 bytes...\"\n- Sched Tux: \"Context switch! PID 42 → PID 57\"\n- Error state: Red shake animation on ENOSYS or dispatch failure\n\n### Implementation Phases\n\n#### Phase 6a: Asset Pipeline and Scene Skeleton\n- [ ] Create `web/art/` directory for penguin sprite sheets (PNG, pixel art)\n- [ ] Draw 7 penguin variants as sprite sheets (7 columns x 3 rows each),\n      reusing tinyclaw's frame layout (idle/walk/type/celebrate/error/sleep)\n- [ ] Draw room backgrounds as tile-able pixel art (VFS, Process, Memory,\n      Network, Block I/O, Gate, Attic) -- simple rectangular rooms with\n      thematic furniture from tinyclaw assets (desks, bookshelves, PCs)\n- [ ] Create `web/js/scene.js` -- scene layout engine (percentage-based\n      coordinates, room rectangles, Z-ordering by Y-position)\n- [ ] Add kernel house container div to `index.html` alongside existing\n      telemetry panels (tab or side-by-side layout)\n\n#### Phase 6b: Character Animation Engine\n- [ ] Port tinyclaw's sprite animation system to vanilla JS:\n      frame-based animation (120ms tick), sprite sheet clipping,\n      directional facing, CSS `image-rendering: pixelated`\n- [ ] Implement penguin state machine: idle → walk → action → idle\n      (action = type/celebrate/error depending on syscall outcome)\n- [ ] Shadow rendering (elliptical shadow beneath each character)\n- [ ] Speech bubble system: positioned above character, auto-expire,\n      shows syscall name / disposition / error\n- [ ] Movement interpolation: smooth walk between rooms when syscall\n      routes to a different subsystem\n\n#### Phase 6c: Wire to Live Telemetry\n- [ ] Map SSE syscall events to character actions:\n      - Event arrives → guest penguin appears in Attic\n      - Dispatcher Tux routes to target room (walk animation)\n      - Target room's Tux performs action (type animation)\n      - Result → celebrate (success) or error (failure) animation\n      - Speech bubble shows syscall name + latency\n- [ ] Map snapshot deltas to room ambient state:\n      - Memory room: block stacks grow/shrink with mem_used\n      - Process room: more guest penguins when context_switches high\n      - VFS room: filing cabinet opens/closes with file_io rate\n      - Gate: dispatch counter drives Dispatcher Tux's busyness\n- [ ] Throttle animation to avoid overwhelming the scene:\n      sample 1-5% of events for character movement, use aggregate\n      counters for ambient effects (room glow, particle density)\n\n#### Phase 6d: Educational Overlays\n- [ ] Clickable rooms: clicking a room opens an explanation panel\n      describing the kernel subsystem (what it does, how kbox intercepts\n      it, link to relevant source file)\n- [ ] Syscall flow arrows: animated dotted lines showing the path\n      from guest → seccomp gate → LKL subsystem → response\n- [ ] \"Narrator mode\": optional text overlays that explain what is\n      happening in plain language (\"The guest process asked to read a\n      file. The dispatcher penguin forwarded this to the VFS room,\n      where File Tux looked up the inode in the ext4 filesystem...\")\n- [ ] Dispatch disposition legend: color-coded\n      (green=CONTINUE/host, blue=LKL emulated, red=ENOSYS rejected)\n\n#### Phase 6e: Integration and Polish\n- [ ] Dark/light theme support for the scene (reuse existing toggle)\n- [ ] Responsive layout: scene scales with viewport, minimum 800x400\n- [ ] Performance budget: scene rendering must not exceed 16ms/frame\n      (60fps), use requestAnimationFrame, batch DOM updates\n- [ ] Tab switching: \"Observatory\" (existing charts) vs \"Kernel House\"\n      (new visualization) vs \"Events\" (existing event feed)\n- [ ] Export: screenshot of kernel house state (canvas.toDataURL)\n- [ ] No new dependencies beyond what is already vendored (Chart.js).\n      All animation is vanilla JS + CSS + canvas/DOM. No Phaser, no\n      React, no build step -- keep it embeddable in the C web server\n\n### Art Asset Licensing\n\nArtwork adapted from externals/star-office-ui-v2 and externals/tinyclaw\nmust respect their licenses. Original penguin sprites created for kbox\nshould be MIT-licensed consistent with the project. Document attribution\nin `web/art/CREDITS.md`.\n\n### What This is NOT\n\n- Not a replacement for the telemetry dashboard (coexists via tabs)\n- Not a game (no user input beyond clicking for info)\n- Not a static diagram (all animation driven by real syscall data)\n- Not framework-dependent (vanilla JS, no build pipeline)\n\n### Open Questions\n\n1. Canvas vs DOM? DOM is simpler for speech bubbles and click handlers,\n   canvas is faster for many sprites. Hybrid (canvas for scene, DOM\n   overlay for bubbles/tooltips) may be the right call.\n2. How many simultaneous guest penguins? At 1% event sampling, bursty\n   workloads might produce 10-50 events/sec. Cap at ~8 visible guest\n   penguins, queue excess.\n3. Should the narrator text be in English only or bilingual (EN/ZH)?\n   The Linux comic is in Chinese; kbox's audience may be broader.\n4. Sprite art: commission pixel art or generate procedurally (like\n   star-office-ui-v2's runtime graphics)? Procedural is simpler to\n   maintain but less charming.\n\n## Performance Baseline (x86_64, node1, Alpine ext4)",
